<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-131-082  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 131 082.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  March 22 1989 n1141* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM UK unveils menu-based Natural Query Language. (productannouncement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   IBM United Kingdom Ltd. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   Menu-based Natural Language Query (Program development software)(product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionNatural Language InterfacesData BasesAccess MethodsLanguage Complexity.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IBM UK UNVEILS MENU-BASED NATURAL LANGUAGE QUERY PACKAGE IBM UK has announceda new Menu-based Natural LAnguage Query package, MBNLQ, for users of IBM ATsor PS/2s.andP;  The program is designed to generate English language dataretrieval queries for accessing databases resident on AS/400, System/36, andSystem/38 hosts.andP;  MBLNQ queries are constructed by choosing from Englishlanguage words and phrases displayed by menus.andP;  The user specifies a choiceby placing a cursor over the required word, and pressing a button on akeyboard or mouse.andP;  The software also provides the user with in-built windowguidance techniques.andP;  IBM says that, bar some exceptions, the same set ofqueries can be used on all three systems.andP;  It also points out that withMBNLQ, there is no need for a user to learn a separate database querylanguage.andP;  The program can un on ATs with 2Mb of memory, or PS/2 Models 50,60, 70, and 80, with 3Mb of memory.andP;  It operates with Version 3.3 and upwardsof IBM's PC-DOS.andP;  Users are also required to have the relevant PC Supportprogram on the host.andP;  MBNLQ is available now, and costs #216.andO;</TEXT></DOC>